{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"422f4d30-476d-4236-9732-2dfe6c62739d","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the Inspector with `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (usually at `http://localhost:5173`) that connects to your server over stdio.\n\n### In the Inspector UI you can:\n- **List Tools** – click \"List Tools\" to see all registered tools\n- **Call Tools** – select a tool, fill in parameters, and execute it\n- **View Logs** – see raw JSON-RPC messages between client and server\n\n### Tips\n- **Environment variables**: pass them with `-e`:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector -e MY_VAR=value dotnet run --project ./src/MyServer.csproj\n  ```\n- **Pre-built binary**: if you have a compiled executable:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector ./MyServer\n  ```\n- **Logging**: write diagnostic logs to **stderr** (not stdout) in your server — stdout is reserved for the MCP JSON-RPC protocol. The Inspector captures and displays stderr output.\n- **Debugging in IDE**: attach your IDE debugger to the `dotnet` process the Inspector spawns, or use `DOTNET_ENVIRONMENT=Development` for verbose logging.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"839e2a0d-e700-4426-8889-ac50abca9913","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about MCP (Model Context Protocol) tooling. I can answer this directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":401,"requestId":"B023:166A0:D534CA:F1E93A:6A027D6A"},"id":"5111b567-8d33-4720-977f-0fcf02a0d20a","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:08:05.562Z","parentId":"73688d64-e3fc-4b9f-b30c-90780bc6167c"}
